So here we see that on average, the correlation between scores is over 80%.

We might wish to understand the reliability of this performance, and so we can bootstrap the samples to see how often the spearman rank correatlion is consistent with this number. For example, we bootstrap the spearman rank correlation for scores 1 and 2:

Code 
library(boot)

spearman_bootstrap <- function(data, indices, col1, col2) {
  # Subset data based on bootstrap sample indices and select only the specified columns
  sampled_data <- data[indices, .(score1 = get(col1), score2 = get(col2))]
  # Calculate the Spearman correlation between the two specified scores
  cor(sampled_data$score1, sampled_data$score2, method = "spearman")
}

# Example of bootstrapping the correlation between the first two PRS scores
prs_columns <- grep("PGS", names(dt), value = TRUE)  # Assuming all PRS scores start with 'PGS'
boot_obj <- boot(data = dt, statistic = spearman_bootstrap, R = 1000, col1 = prs_columns[1], col2=prs_columns[2])
print(boot_obj)

Intra class correlation

Code 
library(irr)
# Assuming each row is an individual and each column is a different PRS measurement
icc_results <- icc(as.matrix(dt[, ..prs_columns]), model = "twoway", type = "consistency")
print(icc_results)
 Single Score Intraclass Correlation

   Model: twoway 
   Type : consistency 

   Subjects = 7393 
     Raters = 27 
   ICC(C,1) = 0.373

 F-Test, H0: r0 = 0 ; H1: r0 > 0 
F(7392,192192) = 17.1 , p = 0 

 95%-Confidence Interval for ICC Population Values:
  0.365 < ICC < 0.381

The intraclass correlation is effectively a random effects model treating individuals and scores both as random effects. We assume that both raters (in this case scores) and individuals are exchangeable, represeting random samples from a larger pool. This is why we chose âtwo-wayâ effectcs. The intraclass coefficient

Understanding the ICC Output

ICC(C,1) = 0.373 - This is the value of the ICC under the model and type specified. An ICC of 0.373 suggests moderate consistency. It means that approximately 37.3% of the total variance in the PRS scores can be attributed to differences between individuals. This level of ICC indicates that while there is some consistency in how individuals are ranked across different PRS scores, there is also a significant amount of variability that is not attributable to differences between individuals.

  • F(7392,192192) = 17.1, p = 0
  • The F statistic is 17.1, and the p-value is extremely small (essentially zero), indicating that the ICC is significantly different from zero. This confirms that the PRS scores are not randomly assigned and that they provide some meaningful differentiation between individuals.
  1. 95%-Confidence Interval for ICC Population Values: 0.365 < ICC < 0.38
    • This confidence interval provides a range of values within which the true ICC is expected to lie with 95% confidence. The narrow range around the ICC estimate further supports its stability and reliability.

Practical Implications

The ICC value of 0.373, while indicating some consistency, is not particularly high, which could imply several things: - There might be a need to investigate whether some PRS scores are not performing as well as others. - The moderate ICC suggests that while the PRS scores can distinguish individuals to some extent, their use might be limited in contexts requiring high reliability (e.g., clinical settings). - Efforts to improve the consistency of these scores might include refining the algorithms or models used to calculate them, or possibly selecting or weighting some scores more than others based on their performance.

In summary, this ICC analysis gives you a quantitative measure of how reliably different PRS scores rank the same individuals. While showing some ability to differentiate between individuals, the consistency is not very strong, indicating room for improvement in PRS methodology or selection.

Code 
prs_columns <- grep("PGS", names(dt), value = TRUE)
dt=data.table(d)
library(data.table)
df=dt
prs_columns <- grep("PGS", names(df), value = TRUE)

# Calculate ranks and determine top/bottom 10%
df[, (prs_columns) := lapply(.SD, rank, ties.method = "average"), .SDcols = prs_columns]
df[, paste0(prs_columns, "_top10") := lapply(.SD, function(x) x > quantile(x, 0.9, names = FALSE)), .SDcols = prs_columns]
df[, paste0(prs_columns, "_bottom10") := lapply(.SD, function(x) x < quantile(x, 0.1, names = FALSE)), .SDcols = prs_columns]

# Prepare to compare pairs
top_10_cols <- grep("_top10", names(df), value = TRUE)
bottom_10_cols <- grep("_bottom10", names(df), value = TRUE)
top_jaccard <- vector("list", length = length(prs_columns))
bottom_jaccard <- vector("list", length = length(prs_columns))

# Compare each pair of scores for top 10% and bottom 10%
for (i in seq_along(prs_columns)) {
  for (j in seq_along(prs_columns)) {
    if (i != j) {
      # Calculate Jaccard index for top 10%
      top_intersection <- sum(df[[top_10_cols[i]]] & df[[top_10_cols[j]]])
      top_union <- sum(df[[top_10_cols[i]]] | df[[top_10_cols[j]]])
      top_jaccard[[i]] <- c(top_jaccard[[i]], top_intersection / top_union)

      # Calculate Jaccard index for bottom 10%
      bottom_intersection <- sum(df[[bottom_10_cols[i]]] & df[[bottom_10_cols[j]]])
      bottom_union <- sum(df[[bottom_10_cols[i]]] | df[[bottom_10_cols[j]]])
      bottom_jaccard[[i]] <- c(bottom_jaccard[[i]], bottom_intersection / bottom_union)
    }
  }
}

# Convert lists to vectors
top_jaccard <- unlist(top_jaccard)
bottom_jaccard <- unlist(bottom_jaccard)

# Prepare data for ggplot
jaccard_data <- data.frame(
  Jaccard = c(top_jaccard, bottom_jaccard),
  Quantile = c(rep("Top 10%", length(top_jaccard)), rep("Bottom 10%", length(bottom_jaccard)))
)

# Create the mirrored density plot
ggplot(jaccard_data, aes(x = Jaccard, fill = Quantile)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  facet_wrap(~Quantile, scales = "free_y", ncol = 1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "red")) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Mirrored Density Plot of Jaccard Indices",
       x = "Jaccard Index",
       y = "Density") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Code 
prs_columns <- grep("PGS", names(dt), value = TRUE)
dt=data.table(d)
library(data.table)
df=dt
prs_columns <- grep("PGS", names(df), value = TRUE)


# Calculate ranks and determine top/bottom 10%
df[, (prs_columns) := lapply(.SD, rank, ties.method = "average"), .SDcols = prs_columns]
df[, paste0(prs_columns, "_top10") := lapply(.SD, function(x) x > quantile(x, 0.9, names = FALSE)), .SDcols = prs_columns]
df[, paste0(prs_columns, "_bottom10") := lapply(.SD, function(x) x < quantile(x, 0.1, names = FALSE)), .SDcols = prs_columns]

# Prepare to compare pairs
top_10_cols <- grep("_top10", names(df), value = TRUE)
bottom_10_cols <- grep("_bottom10", names(df), value = TRUE)
consistency_matrix <- matrix(nrow = length(prs_columns), ncol = length(prs_columns), dimnames = list(prs_columns, prs_columns))

top_mat <- matrix(nrow = length(prs_columns), ncol = length(prs_columns), dimnames = list(prs_columns, prs_columns))

bot_mat <- matrix(nrow = length(prs_columns), ncol = length(prs_columns), dimnames = list(prs_columns, prs_columns))
# Compare each pair of scores for top 10% and bottom 10%
for (i in seq_along(prs_columns)) {
  for (j in seq_along(prs_columns)) {
    if (i != j) {
      # Calculate Jaccard index for top 10%
      top_intersection <- sum(df[[top_10_cols[i]]] & df[[top_10_cols[j]]])
      top_union <- sum(df[[top_10_cols[i]]] | df[[top_10_cols[j]]])
      jaccard_top <- top_intersection / top_union

      # Calculate Jaccard index for bottom 10%
      bottom_intersection <- sum(df[[bottom_10_cols[i]]] & df[[bottom_10_cols[j]]])
      bottom_union <- sum(df[[bottom_10_cols[i]]] | df[[bottom_10_cols[j]]])
      jaccard_bottom <- bottom_intersection / bottom_union

      # Store average of top and bottom Jaccard indices
      consistency_matrix[i, j] <- (jaccard_top + jaccard_bottom) / 2
      top_mat[i, j] <- (jaccard_top)
      bot_mat[i, j] <- (jaccard_bottom)
    }
  }
}
